<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Standing-Single-Arm-Tricep-Kickback">Dumbbell Standing Single-Arm Tricep Kickback</h3>



<p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-standing-single-arm-tricep-kickback" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dumbbell standing single-arm tricep kickbacks</a> are highly beneficial for building and toning the triceps. They contribute to overall muscle strength and upper arm stability through targeted movements.</p>



<p>This is an effective exercise for women because it is versatile and modifiable for a variety of fitness levels. It creates targeted tension in the triceps to improve muscular endurance.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="03541201-Dumbbell-One-Arm-Kickback_Upper-Arms_" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/996118262?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Standing Single-Arm Tricep Kickback Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Begin by selecting a dumbbell that aligns with your fitness goals and level.</li>



<li>Stand with feet slightly staggered (one in front of the other)<strong>,</strong> holding the dumbbell at your side.</li>



<li>Lean forward slightly, maintaining a neutral spine and keeping the back straight.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Exhale as you slowly fully extend your elbow straight behind you, keeping the upper arms stationary.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Hold at the peak of the movement for a count, focusing on engaging the triceps.</li>



<li>Inhale as you slowly bend your elbow to return to the starting position, maintaining control throughout the movement.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">TipsÂ </h4>



<ul>
<li>Start out with some static stretching or arm circles to warm up your triceps.</li>



<li>If you feel <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6857228/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">wrist pain</a>, stop immediately and consult a physical therapist before continuing the exercise.</li>



<li>Focus on controlling the movement and avoid swinging the dumbbell or using momentum during the exercise.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



