<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Chest-Dip">Chest Dip</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/chest-dip" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">chest dip</a> uses a similar movement pattern to the tricep dip but with an increased focus on the chest. Instead of lowering straight down, you tilt forward slightly before lowering, increasing chest muscle engagement.</p>



<p>This exercise is great for improving functional performance as the target muscles support everyday activities involving lifting, pulling, and carrying. It is beneficial for women as it provides comprehensive upper body development while remaining versatile and modifiable.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="02511201-Chest-Dip_Chest" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/969666052?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Chest Dip Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand between a set of parallel dip bars. Hold them with an overhand grip in line with your torso.</li>



<li>Raise yourself so your arms are locked and your body is supported. A box or a suitable raised surface can also used to help. Bend your knees and cross your feet over each other.</li>



<li>Slide your body forward so your chest is in front of your shoulders.</li>



<li>Tilt your body forward so that it is at about a 30-degree angle to the floor.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Bend your elbows to lower your body toward the floor until your upper arms are parallel to the ground.</li>



<li>Hold at the bottom for a count, focusing on squeezing the triceps and chest muscles at the bottom position.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Exhale and push back to the start position, continuing to engage the target muscles.&nbsp;</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your shoulder blades pulled back. This will prevent rounding your shoulders, taking the emphasis off your chest in the bottom position.</li>



<li>Keep your elbows tucked in while squeezing your biceps. This will increase chest activation by providing adduction, moving the chest toward the body&#8217;s midline.</li>



<li>During the momentary pause in the top position, squeeze the handles inward. This creates <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30580468/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">isometric chest contraction</a>, meaning your chest muscles contract without moving.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps</h4>



