<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Tricep-Dumbbell-Kickback">Tricep Dumbbell Kickback</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/tricep-dumbbell-kickback" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">tricep dumbbell kickback</a> primarily targets the triceps, with secondary activation from the wrist flexors and extensors. It involves extending your arm with a dumbbell out behind you while kneeling on a bench.</p>



<p>This exercise is great for women because it is easily modifiable but isolates the triceps to enhance <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6950543/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscle hypertrophy</a>. It also maintains forearm stability when pulling the dumbbell through the range of motion.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Tricep Dumbbell Kickback" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/995312845?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Tricep Dumbbell Kickback Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Select an appropriate dumbbell that allows you to fully extend your elbow several times consecutively.</li>



<li>Place one knee and the same side hand on a bench, slightly in front of the shoulder joint.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Set your standing leg extended down from your hip with your knee slightly bent.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Rest your elbow of the active arm against your ribs with your back straight. Hold your elbow up to align with your back.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core.</li>



<li>Exhale as you straighten the active arm toward your hip, fully extending the elbow. Maintain stability in your back and elbow position throughout the movement.</li>



<li>Hold at the end for a count, squeezing your triceps to maximize engagement.</li>



<li>Slowly bring the arm back through to the starting position, maintaining control.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Avoid twisting your upper body during the movement.</li>



<li>Keep your feet at least hip-width apart to stabilize and reduce injury risk.</li>



<li>Keep your elbow close to your side throughout the exercise.</li>
</ul>



